O surely it shall come to pass that on this spot the Greeks do vie for wreaths in the sweating labour of the pancratium.' 2

There spring for man beside the altar of the peerless ruler Zeus, flowers of renowning Victory which for a very few among men do make signal glory all their lives, and when they be enwrapt in the dark cloud of death, bestow on them the immol-tal fame of a thing well done together with a destiny that cannot fail. These things fell to thee, O son of Lampon, at Nemea, and so thou 'rt come to magnify a lofty·wayed city, come with thy hair crowned with chaplets of all manner of gay flowers, come to the tune of voluptuous flutes and sweet-breathed revel- songs, come to thy native isle, an ensample of eminent might in the pancratium.
